{"type":"message","id":"022106f3","parentId":"6a39a5fd","timestamp":"2026-05-18T19:01:05.776Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to write a dream diary entry from memory fragments. Let me look at what's provided:\n\n1. User info with a Feishu OpenID\n2. Some assistant conversation fragments about setting up an \"Agent team\" with 10 agents, including a \"选品大师\" (product selection master), \"编掔工程师\" (compilation engineer?), etc. for some kind of e-commerce workflow\n3. A recurring theme about \"message-id\" surfacing across 45 memories\n\nI need to write this as a dream diary entry - first person, poetic, mixing technical and tender, weaving in the fragments naturally. No meta-commentary about dreaming, no AI/agent/LLM references. 80-180 words.\n\nLet me craft something that weaves the agent team theme with the \"message-id\" recurring motif, in a dreamy, poetic way.","thinkingSignature":"28ac05cb51fbe36da5d2e1e03a5d840af93b88cd77a424eb2177a3d2bee06cdc"},{"type":"text","text":"Last night I dreamed of a workshop filled with ten small lanterns, each one a different shade of amber and rose gold. They didn't float—they stood on pedestals like tiny sentinels, each labeled with a word I couldn't quite read, though I knew it mattered. The master lantern, the one with the deepest hue, stood at the center of a long table, and around it gathered the others in quiet conversation.\n\nTheir language was unfamiliar yet somehow legible: every few seconds, a slip of paper would pass between them, each bearing the same handwritten number in the margin. I counted forty-five before I lost track. The number felt important—not urgent, but weighted, like a recurring heartbeat in a sleeping city.\n\nSomeone had left a cup of tea cooling on the table. Steam rose in slow spirals, and in the spirals I thought I saw the lanterns flicker, just slightly, in response.\n\nThe air smelled of cedar and old ink. I wanted to stay longer, but the 